%N A119354 Smallest number which does not use digit n-1 written in base n, but does use digit b-1 written in base b for any 1<b<n.
%C A119354 From _Michael S. Branicky_, Sep 08 2025: (Start)
%C A119354 a(36) = 12415603199, a(37) = 1278033119.
%C A119354 a(35) and a(38..oo) > 2*10^9. (End)
%C A119354 From _David A. Corneth_, Sep 10 2025: (Start)
%C A119354 We can ease the search a little bit.
%C A119354 In a search for a(n) if we test some number t and the number t does not have a digit b-1 for some 1 < b < n then we can reset t to the smallest number > t that has a digit b-1. That is set t to t + b-1 - t%b.
%C A119354 For example in a search for a(8) we might be testing 48 and see that 48 = 120_6 which does not contain a digit 6-1. The next number larger than 48 that does contain a digit 5 in base 6 is 48 + 5 - (48%6).
%C A119354 Also if we test a number t in a search for a(n) and see that it has a digit n-1 in base n then we can reset it to the smallest number > t that has no digit n-1 in base n.
%C A119354 For example in our search for a(8) we might be checking 57 = 71_8 which has a digit n-1 in base n. We can reset it to "80_8" = 100_8 = 64 by increasing the 7 by 1 and setting all less significant digits to 0.
%C A119354 In the search for a(35) and a(38) it was sufficient to check just about 1 in 19 numbers this way. (End)
%F A119354 A119352(a(n)) = n and A119352(m) != n for m < a(n). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 12 2015
